		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> LOTR Q&A Rulings from 3/4/04<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617'>Enrique "Max of Tat" Huerta</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 18, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Not for Review<br />
Originally posted 3/4/04<br />
========================<br />
<br />
<br />
Hello All!!<br />
<br />
   Happy Anniversary!!!! This is my 26th LOTR Q&A update and it&#39;s been almost 1 full year since the first one (3/10/03)! Thank you to everyone for helping make this project successful!   <br />
<br />
   Well, there certainly is a lot of LOTR buzz going around these days. (=<br />
<br />
   First off, in case you haven&#39;t heard Return of the King swept the Oscar&#39;s winning 11 of 11 categories in which it was nominated. Good job to all the cast, crew, and who-evers that made the truly enjoyable trilogy of movies. I hear there&#39;s already a book about the story. (=<br />
<br />
   Secondly, there was a new CRD released yesterday with minor entries with the exception of &quot;loops&quot;. It looks like Decipher has tried to tackle the loop situation head on and they&#39;ve come up with a solution. We&#39;ll just have to wait and see how it works. (=<br />
<br />
   Lastly... oh yeah, there was some minor announcment about LOTR Reflections with alternate Ring-bearers, but that&#39;s no biggie. (=<br />
<br />
   See everyone in Vegas!!!<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about Card Rulings:</h3><br />
<b>Mordor Guard says to remove 3 threats when he is discarded. Does this include him being killed, or removed at the end of the regroup phase if your opponent doesn&#39;t or can&#39;t move? [Dustin]</b><br />
<br />
Yes. When you kill a minion, it is discarded. At the end of the turn all remaining minions are discarded. Both of these would trigger the Mordor Guard game text and he would remove 3 Threats.<br />
<br />
As a dedicated [Sauron] player, I can tell you that Mordor Guard is most effective when you play him and Hate someone in the maneuver phase to trigger those threats you just added. That way at the end of the turn of if he&#39;s killed there aren&#39;t any threats to remove.<br />
<br />
<b>Hey Enrique, I thought of another question for you. I guess it might be kind of off the wall but here it goes. There is a MoM card called &quot;You Cannot Pass!&quot; when played during the manuever phase this card prevents a minion from being fierce until the regroup phase. I guess I just don&#39;t understand how that is supposed to work. If a minion is already fierce when the card is played is that minion not fierce anymore? Can another card or effect later on make the minion fierce? I appreciate all your great work. THANKS! [Death Dealer] </b><br />
<br />
You Cannot Pass! has a lasting effect that prevents a minion from being or becoming fierce until the Regroup phase. So if you play it on a minion that IS fierce, they will no longer be fierce (until the Regroup phase). If you play it on a minion that is not fierce, they can not become fierce until the next Regroup phase.<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about Game/Tournament Rulings:</h3><br />
<br />
<b>Shadow Between and Moment of Respite both say at the beginning of the regroup phase. My question is this: can I use their abilities more than once? If so, since it is the beginning of the regroup phase, does the shadow player have a chance to do anything between the usage of these abilities? [Dustin]</b><br />
<br />
Just like cards that act at the beginning of the Fellowship phase, these cards can only be used once per regroup phase and are done before normal Regroup actions. Since they are before normal Regroup actions, they don&#39;t fall under the Action Procedure for Regroup action. In other words, the Shadow player would not be allowed to play No Safe Places (which is a Shadow Regroup event) between the actions of Shadow Between and Moment of Respite. In fact, after using those actions, the first Regroup action would still be the Free Peoples Player&#39;s (FPP).<br />
<br />
<b>Roaming question. Can the roaming # of minions be extended past 9? I ask this cause online A minion was never roaming at site9 no matter even if his # equaled 10 or 11. Thank for ur time [Saircrowe]</b><br />
<br />
<b>Enrique, I have a question for you. I have a ranger deck I&#39;ve been playing recently. It makes minions roaming by increasing their site numbers. My question is can a minion be roaming at site nine? My friends all seem to think that a minion&#39;s site number can not be more than nine. Can you clear this up for me? [Death Dealer] </b><br />
<br />
Sounds like another bug in the online version to me. Yes, there is nothing that prevents a minion&#39;s site number from being greater than 9. If it were to be greater than 9, then the minion would be roaming at every site on the site path.<br />
<br />
<b>Hi, I would like to verify the following combo: Can I play Wulf as a response to a Dunlending Arsonist winning his skirmish and as a response to that same skirmish grab a site with Wulf&#39;s game text ? [Geert (craZee)]</b><br />
<br />
Yes you may. Both the Dunlending Arsonist and Wulf are option actions triggered by winning a skirmish. You may play them in any order. (In fact you would have to play them in the order you mentioned because Wulf isn&#39;t in play until you do the Arsonist&#39;s action.)<br />
<br />
When the Arsonist wins the skirmish you first resolve all mandatory actions to that trigger. After that you may play any optional actions to that trigger in any order. You may first use the DUnlending Arsonist&#39;s action to play Wulf. When that action resolves, you may play any other actions that would trigger on the Arsonist winning the skirmish. At this point, Wulf is a valid action eventhough he wasn&#39;t in play when the Arsonist actually one the skirmish.<br />
<br />
<b>Hi Enrique! Can I use the gametext of Mordor Veteran to boost the strength of another Sauron orc although my opponent is still resolving the Veterans&#39;s skirmish? We were arguing about this since the Veteran is about to be killed and I need to use his ability to boost another minion to overwhelm Frodo. [Gim]</b><br />
<br />
Yes and no. (=<br />
<br />
You may use the Mordor Veteran&#39;s game text to boost the strength of another minion during the MOrdor Veteran&#39;s skirmish. HOWEVER, once that skirmish has resolved, the other minion would no longer get the benefit of the strength bonus. Unless otherwise stated, all effects of an action end at the end of the phase in which that action was played.<br />
<br />
So while you are right in that you can do it... I think you see that it will not have the effect you&#39;re probably hoping for. This is why the FPP&#39;s ability to choose the order that the skirmishes resolve is a huge advantage. <br />
<br />
<b>hi this is in response to your previous ruling:<br />
<i>&quot;This is a pretty basic question, here goes: You can return Merry to hand by spotting 0 possessions, but can you return Pippin to your hand by wounding an imaginary roaming minion twice? [Urthanz] &quot; Yes, the only requirements for Merry and Pippin is that they are not assigned to a skirmish. As long as you pay the costs (returning them to hand) you can carry out as much of the effect as possible and ignore the rest. If there are no roaming minions, that doesn’t prevent you for returning Pippin to hand. (NOTE: Normally you can not &quot;ignore the rest&quot; when playing a card from your hand or discard pile. But Merry’s game text states &quot;up to 2 [Rohan] possessions&quot; so you can choose to play 0. If it did not say &quot;up to&quot; you would not be able to return Merry if there were 0 possesions in the discard pile.)&quot;</i> <br />
This confuses me because you say for merry&#39;s text it&#39;s possible because it says &quot;up to&quot; otherwise you couldn&#39;t return him to hand but with pippin there is no &quot;up to&quot; it just says &quot;to wound a roaming minion twice&quot;...? so how is it that you can return him to hand without carrying it out? if this is true than for they are coming can i discard 3 cards without spotting a minion in my discard to play 0 minions? [Christian]</b><br />
<br />
The rule for carrying out effect of an action is that you must do as much as possible and ignore any effect that you can not do or has no effect. In the case of Pippin discarding, you would wound a roaming minion twice. If there are no roaming minions to wound, you would simply ignore that effect. Just remember, you can&#39;t ignore requirements or costs, just effects that can&#39;t be carried out to their fullest.<br />
<br />
HOWEVER, there are 2 exceptions to this rule of ignore effects. &quot;If you perform an action that has playing a card from your hand or discard pile as part of its effect, you must play that card.&quot; [Comprehensive Rulebook, pg 28] So if you discard 3 cards for They Are Coming, you must play a [Moria] Orc from your discard pile, and it may not be one of the 3 cards you discarded.<br />
<br />
<b>Frodo is overwhelmed by an Orc Officer(Each time a [Sauron] Orc overwhelms a companion add three burdens). There is Sam in play <br />
<br />
Which one goes first: <br />
a- the Sam becomes the ring bearer <br />
b- Orc Oficer adds three burdens. <br />
<br />
I think Sam should be the RB because there has to be a ring bearer in the game at any time. but this is logic. what is the exact rule for it? [kirshamor] </b><br />
<br />
Actually, there are moments in the game when you don&#39;t have a Ring-bearer in play. Or more specifically, your Ring-bearer is in the Dead Pile where adding burdens to them won&#39;t matter.<br />
<br />
If Frodo is overwhelmed by an Orc Officer you must first carry out all mandatory actions that are triggered. Mandatory actions would include resolving any Threat wounds and adding 3 burdens because of the Orc Officer&#39;s game text. When those have resolved, you move on to optional actions that trigger from Frodo being overwhelmed (killed). Sam&#39;s action is an optional Response and would be performed now, AFTER the Orc Officer&#39;s.<br />
<br />
So the Orc Officer would add burdens to a Ring-bearer that isn&#39;t there and then Sam would become the Ring-bearer and not receive those burdens.<br />
<br />
<br />
<h3>Star Wars:CCG Rulings</h3><br />
<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
